<HEADLINE>
Xinhua world economic news summary at 0430 GMT, Sept. 23
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
Crude prices soared over 20 percent Monday, the biggest ever one-
day gain on record, on short squeeze and concerns about the
outlook of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Light, sweet crude for October delivery, which expires Monday,
was up 16.37 dollars to settle at 120.92 dollars a barrel, after
rising as high as of 130.00 dollars per barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. (U.S.-Oil Prices )
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street plunged Monday as investors worried the
U.S. government new bailout plan may not resuscitate a slumping
economy.
</P>
<P>
Investors worried about the uncertainties about the rescue plan's
details and concerned about whether it would provide a lift for
the U.S. economy. (U.S.-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Central Bank of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
announced on Monday that it will set up a facility worth 50
billion dirhams (13.62 billion U.S. dollars) for banks operating
in the Gulf country.
</P>
<P>
The facility was aimed to remedy the situation of inter-bank
deposits in the UAE, which has been affected by the liquidity
constraints in international money markets, said a statement
posted on the bank's website. (UAE-Finance)
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The South Korean government said that is soon likely to
rescue small and medium-sized firms suffering huge losses from
investing in knock-in, knock out (KIKO)options, Korea Herald
reported Tuesday quoting the remarks from Kwon Hyouk-se, a
standing commissioner of the Financial Supervisory Commission
(FSC).
</P>
<P>
"Rescue efforts look possible, considering the government took
the initiative during the 1997-98 financial crisis to save top
venture firms from bankruptcy by fueling liquidity with the
cooperation of KIBO Technology Fund and the Korea Credit
Guarantee Fund," Kwon said. (S.Korea-Rescue Plan)
</P>
